  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national money laundering laws through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish standardized anti-money laundering (AML) principles\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border investigation protocols\n\n3. Compliance Standards\n- Mandatory reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Unified international banking standards\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- Interpol investigations\n- Joint international task forces\n- Coordinated financial sanctions\n- Tracking cross-border financial transactions\n\n5. Regulatory Alignment\n- Countries adapting national laws to international standards\n- Harmonizing legal definitions of money laundering\n- Creating consistent prosecution frameworks\n- Implementing global best practices\n\n6. Technology and Information Exchange\n- Shared digital platforms\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- International financial database collaboration\n- Advanced tracking technologies\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
